  <data key="d0">"LOCATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hills are mentioned in the context of tigers' habitat and space limitations."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5bc15638d83af338881cdee315b5d107</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 17}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 78}, {"level": 2, "cluster": 123}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PREY SPECIES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ANIMAL"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Prey species are the animals at the base of the food chain that are consumed by predators like tigers."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5bc15638d83af338881cdee315b5d107</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 17}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 77}, {"level": 2, "cluster": 121}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SMALLER FOOD&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"FOOD"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Smaller food refers to the primary producers or other organisms that form the base of the food chain and are consumed by prey species."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-5bc15638d83af338881cdee315b5d107</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 17}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 77}, {"level": 2, "cluster": 121}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ENGLISH OAK WOOD&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"LOCATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"English Oak Wood is an example ecosystem used by Elton to illustrate the pyramid of numbers, featuring various levels of animal populations."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37e299e058af586e801321f6b6d35dc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ARCTIC&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"LOCATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Arctic is another example ecosystem mentioned by Elton, showcasing a different pyramid of numbers with crustacea, fish, seals, and polar bears."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37e299e058af586e801321f6b6d35dc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SMALL HERBIVOROUS INSECTS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Small Herbivorous Insects, such as aphids, form the base of the pyramid in the English Oak Wood example, being the most abundant organisms."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37e299e058af586e801321f6b6d35dc</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 17}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 79}, {"level": 2, "cluster": 129}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SPIDERS AND CARNIVOROUS GROUND BEETLES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Spiders and Carnivorous Ground Beetles are the next level in the pyramid of numbers, consuming the small herbivorous insects."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37e299e058af586e801321f6b6d35dc</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 17}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 79}, {"level": 2, "cluster": 129}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SMALL WARBLERS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Small Warblers are part of the middle level of the pyramid, feeding on insects and being preyed upon by larger birds."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37e299e058af586e801321f6b6d35dc</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 17}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 79}, {"level": 2, "cluster": 129}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;HAWKS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Hawks are at the top of the pyramid in the English Oak Wood example, being apex predators that feed on small warblers."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37e299e058af586e801321f6b6d35dc</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 17}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 79}, {"level": 2, "cluster": 128}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;CRUSTACEA&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Crustacea form the base of the pyramid in the Arctic example, being consumed by fish."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37e299e058af586e801321f6b6d35dc</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 17}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 79}, {"level": 2, "cluster": 127}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;FISH&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Fish are the next level in the Arctic pyramid, eating crustacea and being preyed upon by seals."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37e299e058af586e801321f6b6d35dc</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 17}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 79}, {"level": 2, "cluster": 127}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SEALS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Seals are part of the middle level in the Arctic pyramid, feeding on fish and being preyed upon by polar bears."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37e299e058af586e801321f6b6d35dc</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 17}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 79}, {"level": 2, "cluster": 127}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;POLAR BEARS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Polar Bears are at the top of the Arctic pyramid, being apex predators that feed on seals."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37e299e058af586e801321f6b6d35dc</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 17}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 79}, {"level": 2, "cluster": 128}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PREDATORS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Predators are part of the ecological system that regulate animal populations by preying on them, according to Elton's model."&lt;SEP&gt;"Predators refer to animals that hunt and consume other animals, playing a crucial role in regulating population sizes."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-44e345fb0c1f22aa3bf76aed2d40c63d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e37e299e058af586e801321f6b6d35dc</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 17}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 79}, {"level": 2, "cluster": 127}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PATHOGENS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Pathogens are microorganisms that cause disease, contributing to the regulation of animal populations."&lt;SEP&gt;"Pathogens are microorganisms that cause diseases, which also play a role in regulating animal populations, according to Elton's model."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-44e345fb0c1f22aa3bf76aed2d40c63d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e37e299e058af586e801321f6b6d35dc</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 17}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 79}, {"level": 2, "cluster": 129}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PARASITES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Parasites are organisms that live on or in a host organism and derive nutrients at the host's expense, affecting population dynamics."&lt;SEP&gt;"Parasites are organisms that live on or in a host organism and derive nutrients at the host's expense, contributing to population regulation, according to Elton's model."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-44e345fb0c1f22aa3bf76aed2d40c63d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e37e299e058af586e801321f6b6d35dc</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 17}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 79}, {"level": 2, "cluster": 127}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;FOOD SUPPLY&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Food Supply is a critical factor in regulating animal populations, as scarcity can lead to population decline, according to Elton's model."&lt;SEP&gt;"Food Supply refers to the availability of resources that animals depend on for survival, impacting population sizes."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-44e345fb0c1f22aa3bf76aed2d40c63d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e37e299e058af586e801321f6b6d35dc</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 17}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 79}, {"level": 2, "cluster": 127}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;OVERPOPULATION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Overpopulation occurs when the number of animals exceeds the carrying capacity of their environment, leading to resource depletion and potential decline."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37e299e058af586e801321f6b6d35dc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;EXTINCTION&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Extinction is the permanent disappearance of a species, which can occur if a population is unable to maintain itself."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37e299e058af586e801321f6b6d35dc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;BALANCE OF ANIMAL NUMBERS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Balance of Animal Numbers refers to the equilibrium maintained in a given area, ensuring sustainable population levels."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37e299e058af586e801321f6b6d35dc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;VAST NUMBERS OF SMALL HERBIVOROUS INSECTS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Vast Numbers of Small Herbivorous Insects form the base of the pyramid in the English Oak Wood example, being the most abundant organisms."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37e299e058af586e801321f6b6d35dc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;LARGE NUMBER OF SPIDERS AND CARNIVOROUS GROUND BEETLES&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Large Number of Spiders and Carnivorous Ground Beetles are the next level in the pyramid of numbers, consuming the small herbivorous insects."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37e299e058af586e801321f6b6d35dc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;FAIR NUMBER OF SMALL WARBLERS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Fair Number of Small Warblers are part of the middle level of the pyramid, feeding on insects and being preyed upon by larger birds."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37e299e058af586e801321f6b6d35dc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ONE OR TWO HAWKS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"One or Two Hawks are at the top of the pyramid in the English Oak Wood example, being apex predators that feed on small warblers."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37e299e058af586e801321f6b6d35dc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;COPIOUS NUMBERS OF CRUSTACEA&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Copious Numbers of Crustacea form the base of the pyramid in the Arctic example, being consumed by fish."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37e299e058af586e801321f6b6d35dc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SMALLER NUMBER OF POLAR BEARS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Smaller Number of Polar Bears are at the top of the Arctic pyramid, being apex predators that feed on seals."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-e37e299e058af586e801321f6b6d35dc</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;LEMMINGS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Lemmings are a specific type of rodent that are often cited in discussions of animal population regulation."&lt;SEP&gt;"Lemmings are the subject of Elton's and Collett's writings, known for their supposed mass migrations and suicides."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-44e345fb0c1f22aa3bf76aed2d40c63d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f90dce699c970ebe061d69b3d6b78082</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 17}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 78}, {"level": 2, "cluster": 125}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;COLLETT'S BOOK&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Collett's Book is a reference work that Elton read, providing information about lemming behavior, particularly the 'lemming year' phenomenon."&lt;SEP&gt;"Collett's book is a source of information on lemming behavior, though its accuracy is questionable."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-44e345fb0c1f22aa3bf76aed2d40c63d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f90dce699c970ebe061d69b3d6b78082</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 17}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 78}, {"level": 2, "cluster": 125}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ECOLOGISTS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Ecologists are scientists who study ecosystems and were spurred by Elton's book to search for the rules governing the regulation of animal numbers."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-44e345fb0c1f22aa3bf76aed2d40c63d</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 17}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 78}, {"level": 2, "cluster": 123}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;PHYSIOLOGISTS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"ORGANIZATION"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Physiologists are scientists who study the functions and processes of living organisms, motivated by Cannon's concept of homeostasis to search for the rules that regulate processes within humans and other creatures."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-44e345fb0c1f22aa3bf76aed2d40c63d</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 17}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 78}, {"level": 2, "cluster": 123}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ANIMAL ECOLOGY&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Animal Ecology is the journal or publication where Elton wrote about lemming behavior."&lt;SEP&gt;"Animal Ecology is the title of Elton's book, where he discussed his model of regulating animal numbers."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-44e345fb0c1f22aa3bf76aed2d40c63d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f90dce699c970ebe061d69b3d6b78082</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 17}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 78}, {"level": 2, "cluster": 123}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;LEMMING YEAR&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"A Lemming Year is a phenomenon described in Collett's book where large numbers of lemmings are observed, often leading to misconceptions about their behavior."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-44e345fb0c1f22aa3bf76aed2d40c63d</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 17}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 78}, {"level": 2, "cluster": 125}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;SUICIDAL LEMMINGS MYTH&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"The Suicidal Lemmings Myth is a misconception about lemming behavior that was fostered by Elton's interpretation of Collett's book."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-44e345fb0c1f22aa3bf76aed2d40c63d</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 17}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 78}, {"level": 2, "cluster": 123}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;WALT DISNEY FILM WHITE WILDERNESS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"White Wilderness is a 1958 film that inaccurately depicted lemmings jumping to their deaths."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-f90dce699c970ebe061d69b3d6b78082</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;ACADEMY AWARD&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"EVENT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Academy Award is the award that the 1958 Walt Disney film White Wilderness won."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-f90dce699c970ebe061d69b3d6b78082</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;JACQUES MONOD AND FRANÇOIS JACOB&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"PERSON"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Jacques Monod and François Jacob are scientists who made a statement about the universality of biological principles across different species."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-f90dce699c970ebe061d69b3d6b78082</data>
  <data key="d3">[{"level": 0, "cluster": 16}, {"level": 1, "cluster": 75}]</data>
</node>
<node id="&quot;REGULATION OF ANIMAL NUMBERS&quot;">
  <data key="d0">"CONCEPT"</data>
  <data key="d1">"Regulation of animal numbers is a topic discussed by Elton and Cannon, referring to the control of population sizes in nature and applied fields."&lt;SEP&gt;"Regulation of animal numbers is a topic discussed by Elton, Cannon, and others, referring to the control of population sizes in nature and applied fields."&lt;SEP&gt;"Regulation of animal numbers is a topic discussed by Elton, referring to the control of population sizes in nature and applied fields."</data>
  <data key="d2">chunk-f90dce699c970ebe061d69b3d6b78082</data>
