  <data key="d5">"Female Music Theater Singers often use chest register in their performances, extending it beyond the traditional classical shift."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-c53f290cfdb325aa86cba150df1616e4</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;CHEST REGISTER&quot;" target="&quot;TA DOMINANT MODE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">6.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"TA Dominant Mode is used in Chest Register."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-c53f290cfdb325aa86cba150df1616e4</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;CHEST REGISTER&quot;" target="&quot;MODAL VOICE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Modal Voice is used in Chest Register."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-c53f290cfdb325aa86cba150df1616e4</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;BELT VOICE&quot;" target="&quot;SPEECH EXERCISES&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Belt Voice can be developed using speech exercises, which are specifically designed to enhance the mix/belt sound in music theater singing."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-c53f290cfdb325aa86cba150df1616e4</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;CHEST REGISTER DOMINANT SINGING&quot;" target="&quot;SPEAKING&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"chest register dominant singing and speaking use the throat muscle, specifically the thyroarytenoid, in a very similar way, indicating a close relationship in vocal technique."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-3f3c8f816c3f21505f72df4a8ef298e3</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;SINGING VOICE&quot;" target="&quot;MUSIC THEATER SINGING&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Singing Voice is used in Music Theater Singing."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-c53f290cfdb325aa86cba150df1616e4</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;SINGING VOICE&quot;" target="&quot;VOICING&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Voicing is the act of producing the Singing Voice."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-c53f290cfdb325aa86cba150df1616e4</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;CLASSICAL SINGING&quot;" target="&quot;PASSAGGIO&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"In classical singing, the use or addition of 'head' voice at the passaggio is increased more than in music theater singing."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-e4e181dd5099e0ad2640bc3700a9eb29</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;BELT SOUND&quot;" target="&quot;POP/ROCK MUSICAL&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"belt sound is a vocal technique commonly used in pop/rock musicals, highlighting the relationship between the technique and the genre of music."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-3f3c8f816c3f21505f72df4a8ef298e3</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;BELT SOUND&quot;" target="&quot;SPEECH EXERCISES&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"speech exercises are used to create the mix/belt sound, establishing a direct link between these two concepts."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-3f3c8f816c3f21505f72df4a8ef298e3</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;BELT SOUND&quot;" target="&quot;CLASSICAL VOCAL PRODUCTION&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"classical vocal production is distinct from the belt sound, indicating a contrast in vocal techniques."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-3f3c8f816c3f21505f72df4a8ef298e3</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;BELT SOUND&quot;" target="&quot;HIGH BELT&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"high belt is a term used to describe the extension of the belt voice to higher octaves, which is a specific application of the belt sound."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-3f3c8f816c3f21505f72df4a8ef298e3</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;MUSIC THEATER SINGING&quot;" target="&quot;CLASSICAL SINGING TECHNIQUE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">12.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Music Theater Singing and Classical Singing Technique are distinct styles of singing with different techniques and ranges, often used in different contexts."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-c53f290cfdb325aa86cba150df1616e4</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;MUSIC THEATER SINGING&quot;" target="&quot;MIDDLE C&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Music Theater Singing involves singing beyond Middle C."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-c53f290cfdb325aa86cba150df1616e4</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;MUSIC THEATER SINGING&quot;" target="&quot;POPULAR SINGING&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Popular Singing is a form of Music Theater Singing."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-c53f290cfdb325aa86cba150df1616e4</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;MUSIC THEATER SINGING&quot;" target="&quot;SINGING PERFORMANCE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Singing Performance involves Music Theater Singing."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-c53f290cfdb325aa86cba150df1616e4</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;MUSIC THEATER SINGING&quot;" target="&quot;MUSICAL THEATER PERFORMANCE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Musical Theater Performance involves Music Theater Singing."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-c53f290cfdb325aa86cba150df1616e4</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;CLASSICAL SHIFT&quot;" target="&quot;MIX REGISTER&quot;">
  <data key="d4">10.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The Classical Shift marks the point where singers traditionally shift from chest to head register, while Mix Register is used in music theater to extend chest register."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-c53f290cfdb325aa86cba150df1616e4</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;CLASSICAL SHIFT&quot;" target="&quot;VOICE SHIFT&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Voice Shift includes the Classical Shift."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-c53f290cfdb325aa86cba150df1616e4</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;MIX REGISTER&quot;" target="&quot;VOIX MIXTE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">14.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Mix Register in music theater is different from Voix Mixte in classical singing, as the former has a predominance of chest register while the latter has a predominance of head register."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-c53f290cfdb325aa86cba150df1616e4</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;VOIX MIXTE&quot;" target="&quot;HEAD REGISTER&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Head Register is predominant in Voix Mixte."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-c53f290cfdb325aa86cba150df1616e4</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;VOIX MIXTE&quot;" target="&quot;CLASSICAL VOICE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Classical Voice is related to Voix Mixte."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-c53f290cfdb325aa86cba150df1616e4</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;MUSIC THEATER MIX&quot;" target="&quot;BELT SINGING&quot;">
  <data key="d4">18.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Music Theater Mix is a blend of head and chest registers with a predominance of chest register, used in belt singing in music theater."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-c53f290cfdb325aa86cba150df1616e4</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;MUSIC THEATER MIX&quot;" target="&quot;HEAD REGISTER&quot;">
  <data key="d4">6.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Music theater mix uses more chest register than the head register, which is lighter and more spoken."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-e4e181dd5099e0ad2640bc3700a9eb29</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;MUSIC THEATER MIX&quot;" target="&quot;CLASSICAL _VOIX MIXTE_&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Music theater mix is more extensive in use compared to classical _voix mixte_, which balances chest and head registers."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-e4e181dd5099e0ad2640bc3700a9eb29</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;BELT SINGING&quot;" target="&quot;CALLING VOICE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Belt Singing is an extension of the calling voice, which is the natural speaking voice of a singer, used in music theater performances."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-c53f290cfdb325aa86cba150df1616e4</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;HEAD REGISTER&quot;" target="&quot;BELTING&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Belting is a vocal technique that uses the head register for a powerful, resonant sound, distinct from the lighter qualities of the head register."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-e4e181dd5099e0ad2640bc3700a9eb29</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;VOCAL PEDAGOGUE&quot;" target="&quot;RICHARD MILLER&quot;">
  <data key="d4">10.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Richard Miller is a Vocal Pedagogue."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-c53f290cfdb325aa86cba150df1616e4</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;OPERATIC SINGING&quot;" target="&quot;CLASSICAL VOICE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Operatic Singing is a form of Classical Voice."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-c53f290cfdb325aa86cba150df1616e4</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;YOUNGER, LESS EXPERIENCED SINGERS&quot;" target="&quot;TECHNIQUE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Younger, less experienced singers are more prone to technical issues or phonotrauma due to improper technique or excessive strain."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-e4e181dd5099e0ad2640bc3700a9eb29</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;MORE MATURE SINGERS WITH PROFESSIONAL PERFORMING CAREERS&quot;" target="&quot;OVERUSE AND MISUSE INJURIES&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"More mature singers with professional performing careers are more likely to experience overuse and misuse injuries like muscle tension dysphonia, edema, and GERD."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-e4e181dd5099e0ad2640bc3700a9eb29</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;TECHNIQUE&quot;" target="&quot;PHONOTRAUMA&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Improper technique or excessive strain can lead to phonotrauma, including nodules, edema, and contact ulcers."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-e4e181dd5099e0ad2640bc3700a9eb29</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;PHONOTRAUMA&quot;" target="&quot;NODULES&quot;">
  <data key="d4">6.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Nodules are a form of phonotrauma, which affects the vocal folds due to improper technique or excessive strain."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-e4e181dd5099e0ad2640bc3700a9eb29</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;PHONOTRAUMA&quot;" target="&quot;EDEMA&quot;">
  <data key="d4">6.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Edema is a form of phonotrauma, which affects the vocal folds due to improper technique or excessive strain."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-e4e181dd5099e0ad2640bc3700a9eb29</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;PHONOTRAUMA&quot;" target="&quot;CONTACT ULCERS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">6.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Contact ulcers are a form of phonotrauma, which affects the vocal folds due to improper technique or excessive strain."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-e4e181dd5099e0ad2640bc3700a9eb29</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;ACUTE INJURIES&quot;" target="&quot;ILLNESS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">6.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Illness can lead to acute injuries in the vocal folds, affecting a singer's performance and health."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-e4e181dd5099e0ad2640bc3700a9eb29</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;OVERUSE AND MISUSE INJURIES&quot;" target="&quot;MUSCLE TENSION DYSPHONIA&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Muscle tension dysphonia is a form of overuse and misuse injury, resulting from prolonged or improper use of the voice."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-e4e181dd5099e0ad2640bc3700a9eb29</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;OVERUSE AND MISUSE INJURIES&quot;" target="&quot;GERD&quot;">
  <data key="d4">7.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"GERD is a form of overuse and misuse injury, resulting from prolonged or improper use of the voice."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-e4e181dd5099e0ad2640bc3700a9eb29</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;STROBOSCOPIC EVALUATION&quot;" target="&quot;ABNORMAL VOCAL FOLD FINDINGS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Stroboscopic evaluation can reveal abnormal vocal fold findings in professional vocal athletes."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-e4e181dd5099e0ad2640bc3700a9eb29</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;PROFESSIONAL VOCAL ATHLETES&quot;" target="&quot;ABNORMAL VOCAL FOLD FINDINGS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Somewhere between 35 percent and 100 percent of professional vocal athletes have abnormal vocal fold findings on stroboscopic evaluation."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-e4e181dd5099e0ad2640bc3700a9eb29</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;PROFESSIONAL VOCAL ATHLETES&quot;" target="&quot;LARYNGEAL PATHOLOGIES&quot;">
  <data key="d4">16.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Professional Vocal Athletes are at risk of having abnormal vocal fold findings due to the nature of their work, which can affect their performance."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dfad2649adb856c44a11ebf094e0805e</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;PROFESSIONAL VOCAL ATHLETES&quot;" target="&quot;STUDIES&quot;">
  <data key="d4">27.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Professional Vocal Athletes are subjects of numerous studies that document the prevalence of abnormal vocal fold findings, contributing to the field of vocal health."&lt;SEP&gt;"Studies document the prevalence of abnormal vocal fold findings among Professional Vocal Athletes, highlighting the importance of understanding these conditions."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-dfad2649adb856c44a11ebf094e0805e</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
