  <data key="d4">18.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"In the Pyramid of Numbers, tigers are positioned at the apex, representing a smaller number compared to the abundant prey at the base."&lt;SEP&gt;"In the Pyramid of Numbers, tigers are positioned at the apex, representing a smaller number compared to the number of prey at the base."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-5bc15638d83af338881cdee315b5d107</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;TIGERS&quot;" target="&quot;ONE HILL CANNOT SHELTER TWO TIGERS.&quot; &quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"This phrase emphasizes the scarcity of suitable habitats and resources for tigers, which limits their population to one per habitat."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-5bc15638d83af338881cdee315b5d107</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;TIGERS&quot;" target="&quot;APEX PREDATORS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">36.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Tigers are examples of apex predators, which are less abundant due to their position at the top of the food chain."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-5bc15638d83af338881cdee315b5d107</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;TIGERS&quot;" target="&quot;ECOLOGICAL BALANCE&quot;">
  <data key="d4">35.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Tigers, as apex predators, help maintain ecological balance by controlling the population of prey species."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-5bc15638d83af338881cdee315b5d107</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;TIGERS&quot;" target="&quot;TROPHIC LEVELS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Tigers are apex predators, occupying the highest trophic level in a food chain, while prey are typically at lower trophic levels."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-5bc15638d83af338881cdee315b5d107</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;TIGERS&quot;" target="&quot;HILLS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">8.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Tigers, as apex predators, require sufficient space and resources, which are limited by the number of hills available."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-5bc15638d83af338881cdee315b5d107</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;TIGERS&quot;" target="&quot;PREY SPECIES&quot;">
  <data key="d4">10.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Tigers, as apex predators, rely on prey species for sustenance, which are typically more abundant at the base of the food chain."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-5bc15638d83af338881cdee315b5d107</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;TIGERS&quot;" target="&quot;SMALLER FOOD&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Tigers, as apex predators, depend on the availability of smaller food, which includes primary producers and other organisms at the base of the food chain."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-5bc15638d83af338881cdee315b5d107</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;TIGERS&quot;" target="&quot;PRIMARY PRODUCERS&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"Tigers, as apex predators, depend on the availability of smaller food, which includes primary producers and other organisms at the base of the food chain."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-5bc15638d83af338881cdee315b5d107</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
<edge source="&quot;TIGERS&quot;" target="&quot;FEASIBILITY OF GETTING ENOUGH OF THE SMALLER FOOD&quot;">
  <data key="d4">9.0</data>
  <data key="d5">"The abundance of prey species is crucial for the survival and growth of animals at the base of the food chain."</data>
  <data key="d6">chunk-5bc15638d83af338881cdee315b5d107</data>
  <data key="d7">1</data>
</edge>
